      "rawMarkdown": "# 74. Canonize\n\n**Pronunciation:** KAN-ə-nyze\n**Part of speech:** Verb\n**Core meaning:** To officially declare someone a saint; more generally, to glorify or treat someone as perfect.\n**Bangla meaning:** সন্ত ঘোষণা করা, মহিমান্বিত করা, অতিরিক্ত পূজ্য করে তোলা\n**Root story:** From **canon**, meaning an official rule, list, or accepted standard. To canonize someone is to put that person into an official sacred list.\n**Simple explanation:** In religion, canonize means declaring a person a saint. In general GRE usage, it can mean treating a person, writer, or idea as beyond criticism.\n**Memory hook:** **Canonize = put into the sacred canon/list.**\n**GRE synonyms:** glorify, venerate, exalt, sanctify, idolize\n**Basic synonyms:** praise highly, honor, worship, celebrate\n**Antonyms:** condemn, criticize, denounce, vilify, disparage\n**Common usage:** canonize a saint, canonize a leader, canonize an author, canonize a political figure\n**Confusing word:** **Canonize ≠ Cannon.** Canon = official collection/rule; cannon = large gun.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Easy examples**\n\n1. The church canonized the priest.\n   Meaning: The priest was declared a saint.\n   Bangla: পুরোহিতকে সন্ত ঘোষণা করা হলো।\n\n2. People tried to canonize the national hero.\n   Meaning: They treated him as almost perfect.\n   Bangla: নায়ককে অতিরিক্ত মহিমান্বিত করা।\n\n3. The author was canonized after death.\n   Meaning: He was treated as a great accepted figure.\n   Bangla: মৃত্যুর পর মহিমান্বিত।\n\n**GRE / Academic examples**\n\n4. Historians warned against canonizing leaders without examining their failures.\n   Meaning: Leaders should not be treated as flawless.\n   Bangla: নেতাকে নিখুঁত হিসেবে দেখানো উচিত নয়।\n\n5. The movement canonized its founder as a symbol of moral courage.\n   Meaning: The founder was glorified.\n   Bangla: প্রতিষ্ঠাতাকে মহিমান্বিত করা।\n\n6. Literary critics helped canonize the novelist as a central figure in modern fiction.\n   Meaning: They made the novelist part of accepted literary greatness.\n   Bangla: সাহিত্যিককে মূলধারার মহত্ত্বে স্থান দেওয়া।\n\n7. The documentary refuses to canonize the scientist; it presents both brilliance and flaws.\n   Meaning: It does not glorify him blindly.\n   Bangla: অন্ধভাবে মহিমান্বিত করে না।\n\n**Real-world / paper-style examples**\n\n8. In religious history, canonization often follows a formal investigation of a person’s life and legacy.\n   Meaning: Official sainthood requires examination.\n   Bangla: সন্ত ঘোষণার আগে যাচাই।\n\n9. In political writing, societies sometimes canonize revolutionary figures after independence.\n   Meaning: They turn them into sacred national symbols.\n   Bangla: বিপ্লবী ব্যক্তিকে জাতীয় প্রতীক বানানো।\n\n10. In literary studies, canonizing certain authors can marginalize voices outside the accepted tradition.\n    Meaning: Choosing “great” authors may exclude others.\n    Bangla: কিছু লেখককে মানদণ্ড করলে অন্যরা বাদ পড়ে।\n\n## GRE synonym examples\n\n1. The speech tried to **glorify** war.\n2. The community continued to **venerate** the reformer.\n3. The biography **exalted** the king’s courage.\n4. The ritual seemed to **sanctify** the leader’s authority.\n5. Fans often **idolize** successful athletes.\n6. The poem **glorified** rural poverty as noble.\n7. Citizens **venerated** the founder’s memory.\n8. The monument **exalted** sacrifice.\n9. The ceremony **sanctified** the site.\n10. Young artists **idolized** the painter.\n11. Propaganda can **glorify** flawed leaders.\n12. The villagers **venerated** the saint.\n13. The article **exalted** innovation above ethics.\n14. Tradition **sanctified** the old custom.\n15. The public began to **idolize** the activist.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Canonize = officially glorify = সন্ত ঘোষণা / মহিমান্বিত করা**\n\n---",
