      "rawMarkdown": "# 76. Chicanery\n\n**Pronunciation:** shi-KAY-nuh-ree\n**Part of speech:** Noun\n**Core meaning:** Dishonest trickery used to deceive people.\n**Bangla meaning:** ছলনা, প্রতারণা, কৌশলী ধোঁকাবাজি\n**Root story:** From French *chicaner*, meaning to quibble, argue dishonestly, or use legal tricks. The original feeling is “using clever tricks instead of honest reasoning.”\n**Simple explanation:** Chicanery is not a simple lie only. It is clever, manipulative dishonesty, often in politics, business, law, or negotiation.\n**Memory hook:** **Chicanery = cheat + trickery.**\n**GRE synonyms:** deceit, trickery, fraud, duplicity, subterfuge, guile\n**Basic synonyms:** cheating, dishonesty, scam, manipulation\n**Antonyms:** honesty, fairness, integrity, transparency, candor\n**Common usage:** political chicanery, legal chicanery, financial chicanery, bureaucratic chicanery\n**Confusing word:** **Chicanery ≠ Chic.** Chic = stylish; chicanery = dishonest trickery.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Easy examples**\n\n1. The salesman used chicanery to sell fake products.\n2. The villagers were angry after discovering the official’s chicanery.\n3. Chicanery may bring quick profit, but it destroys trust.\n\n**Medium examples**\n\n4. The company’s accounting chicanery made its profits look larger than they really were.\n5. The lawyer criticized the contract as a product of legal chicanery rather than fair negotiation.\n6. Voters became skeptical after years of political chicanery.\n7. The manager’s chicanery allowed him to hide losses from investors.\n\n**GRE / Academic examples**\n\n8. The historian argued that the treaty was less a diplomatic achievement than an act of imperial chicanery.\n9. In corporate governance research, financial chicanery is often linked with weak oversight.\n10. The report exposed a pattern of bureaucratic chicanery designed to delay public access to information.\n\n## GRE synonym examples\n\n1. The witness exposed the company’s **deceit**.\n2. The proposal succeeded through **trickery**, not merit.\n3. The audit revealed widespread **fraud**.\n4. His **duplicity** made allies doubt every promise he made.\n5. The minister used **subterfuge** to hide the real policy goal.\n6. Her **guile** allowed her to manipulate the negotiation.\n7. The candidate’s **deceit** damaged his credibility.\n8. The magician’s act was harmless **trickery**, unlike political manipulation.\n9. The investors sued after discovering financial **fraud**.\n10. The spy’s **duplicity** endangered the mission.\n11. The government used procedural **subterfuge** to avoid debate.\n12. The villain relied on **guile** rather than force.\n13. The court condemned the businessman’s **deceit**.\n14. The scheme depended on careful **trickery**.\n15. The scandal revealed both **fraud** and institutional negligence.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Chicanery = clever dishonest trickery = ছলনা / প্রতারণা**\n\n---",
