      "rawMarkdown": "# 83. Deference\n\n**Pronunciation:** DEF-er-əns\n**Part of speech:** Noun\n**Core meaning:** Respectful submission to another person’s opinion, authority, age, or status.\n**Bangla meaning:** সম্মান প্রদর্শন, শ্রদ্ধাপূর্ণ আনুগত্য, মান্যতা\n**Root story:** From Latin/French roots meaning “to yield” or “to carry down/away.” Deference suggests yielding respectfully to someone else.\n**Simple explanation:** Deference is respect shown by listening, yielding, or behaving politely toward someone considered senior, expert, or authoritative.\n**Memory hook:** **Deference = defer to someone with respect.**\n**GRE synonyms:** respect, submission, regard, reverence, obeisance\n**Basic synonyms:** honor, politeness, respectfulness\n**Antonyms:** disrespect, defiance, contempt, insolence, disregard\n**Common usage:** show deference, out of deference, deference to elders, judicial deference\n**Confusing word:** **Deference ≠ Difference.** Deference = respect; difference = distinction.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Easy examples**\n\n1. He showed deference to his teacher.\n2. Out of deference to his parents, he listened quietly.\n3. The students stood in deference to the guest.\n\n**Medium examples**\n\n4. The junior researcher spoke with deference to the senior professor.\n5. The court showed deference to the earlier ruling.\n6. Excessive deference to authority can discourage honest criticism.\n7. In many cultures, deference to elders is considered proper behavior.\n\n**GRE / Academic examples**\n\n8. The article argues that democratic debate requires respect but not blind deference.\n9. In administrative law, judicial deference can shape how courts review agency decisions.\n10. The organization’s culture of deference prevented employees from questioning unsafe practices.\n\n## GRE synonym examples\n\n1. She treated the judge with **respect**.\n2. The regime demanded total **submission**.\n3. He showed deep **regard** for his mentor.\n4. The villagers held the old teacher in **reverence**.\n5. The servant made an **obeisance** before the king.\n6. Mutual **respect** improves collaboration.\n7. Forced **submission** is not genuine loyalty.\n8. The committee had high **regard** for her expertise.\n9. The shrine was visited with **reverence**.\n10. Ritual **obeisance** symbolized loyalty.\n11. He listened with **respect**, even when he disagreed.\n12. The defeated army offered **submission**.\n13. The scholar’s **regard** for evidence was admirable.\n14. The leader was treated with excessive **reverence**.\n15. The ceremony required formal **obeisance**.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Deference = respectful yielding = সম্মান প্রদর্শন**\n\n---",
