      "rawMarkdown": "# 87. Equivocate\n\n**Pronunciation:** ih-KWIV-uh-kayt\n**Part of speech:** Verb\n**Core meaning:** To use vague or ambiguous language to avoid telling the truth or making a clear commitment.\n**Bangla meaning:** দ্ব্যর্থক কথা বলা, অস্পষ্টভাবে উত্তর দেওয়া, এড়িয়ে যাওয়া\n**Root story:** From Latin **aequus** = equal + **vox** = voice. Equivocate originally suggests giving words “equal voices,” so the meaning can go in more than one direction.\n**Simple explanation:** When someone equivocates, they avoid a direct answer by speaking unclearly.\n**Memory hook:** **Equivocate = equal voices = unclear answer.**\n**GRE synonyms:** prevaricate, hedge, evade, be ambiguous, dodge, quibble\n**Basic synonyms:** avoid, speak vaguely, not answer directly\n**Antonyms:** answer clearly, state directly, clarify, be candid\n**Common usage:** equivocate on policy, equivocate under pressure, refuse to equivocate, political equivocation\n**Confusing word:** **Equivocate ≠ Advocate.** Equivocate = avoid clear answer; advocate = support publicly.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Easy examples**\n\n1. The politician equivocated when asked about taxes.\n2. Please do not equivocate; answer yes or no.\n3. He equivocated because he was afraid of criticism.\n\n**Medium examples**\n\n4. The manager equivocated about whether layoffs were planned.\n5. The witness equivocated under cross-examination.\n6. Instead of admitting failure, the official equivocated for several minutes.\n7. Her answer sounded polite but equivocated on the central issue.\n\n**GRE / Academic examples**\n\n8. The article criticizes leaders who equivocate during public health crises instead of providing clear guidance.\n9. In diplomatic negotiations, states may equivocate to preserve flexibility.\n10. The researcher refused to equivocate: the data clearly contradicted the original hypothesis.\n\n## GRE synonym examples\n\n1. The official tried to **prevaricate** during the interview.\n2. The CEO continued to **hedge** on the merger question.\n3. The witness attempted to **evade** the question.\n4. The statement was deliberately **ambiguous**.\n5. The minister tried to **dodge** responsibility.\n6. Lawyers sometimes **quibble** over technical wording.\n7. He began to **prevaricate** when asked for evidence.\n8. Investors dislike executives who **hedge** too often.\n9. The candidate **evaded** questions about corruption.\n10. The treaty used **ambiguous** language.\n11. She tried to **dodge** the accusation.\n12. The critic accused him of **quibbling** instead of answering.\n13. The witness’s attempt to **prevaricate** angered the judge.\n14. The report **hedged** its conclusion.\n15. He **evaded** the central question completely.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Equivocate = avoid clear truth with vague words = দ্ব্যর্থক কথা বলা**\n\n---",
