      "rawMarkdown": "# 88. Polarize\n\n**Pronunciation:** POH-luh-ryze\n**Part of speech:** Verb\n**Core meaning:** To divide people into sharply opposing groups.\n**Bangla meaning:** বিভক্ত করা, দুই মেরুতে ভাগ করা, তীব্র মতভেদ সৃষ্টি করা\n**Root story:** From **pole**, meaning opposite ends. Polarize means to push opinions toward opposite poles.\n**Simple explanation:** A polarizing issue does not merely create disagreement; it divides people strongly into opposing sides.\n**Memory hook:** **Polarize = push people to opposite poles.**\n**GRE synonyms:** divide, split, separate, factionalize, alienate\n**Basic synonyms:** divide, separate, create conflict\n**Antonyms:** unite, reconcile, integrate, harmonize, bridge\n**Common usage:** polarize society, polarizing debate, polarized politics, polarizing issue\n**Confusing word:** **Polarize ≠ Popularize.** Polarize = divide; popularize = make popular.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Easy examples**\n\n1. The issue polarized the class.\n2. The speech polarized voters.\n3. Social media can polarize people.\n\n**Medium examples**\n\n4. The new law polarized the country into supporters and opponents.\n5. Instead of building consensus, the campaign polarized public opinion.\n6. A polarizing leader may inspire loyalty and hostility at the same time.\n7. The debate over energy policy polarized urban and rural communities.\n\n**GRE / Academic examples**\n\n8. The study examines how misinformation can polarize democratic societies.\n9. In political science, polarizing rhetoric is often associated with declining institutional trust.\n10. The reform polarized experts: some praised its ambition, while others condemned its risks.\n\n## GRE synonym examples\n\n1. The crisis **divided** the nation.\n2. The argument **split** the committee.\n3. The wall **separated** the two neighborhoods.\n4. Sectarian politics can **factionalize** a society.\n5. Harsh policies may **alienate** moderate voters.\n6. The ruling **divided** public opinion.\n7. The scandal **split** the party.\n8. Economic inequality **separated** communities socially.\n9. Ideological disputes **factionalized** the movement.\n10. The speech **alienated** many supporters.\n11. The proposal **divided** experts.\n12. The issue **split** families and friendships.\n13. Poor communication **separated** management from workers.\n14. Internal rivalry **factionalized** the organization.\n15. The decision **alienated** young voters.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Polarize = divide into opposite sides = বিভক্ত করা**\n\n---",
